The projects outputs included an 11-episode podcast series, a bimonthly newsletter series, an online resource library with more than 400 entries, a magazine article, a two-day unconference, and a guide and toolkit for storyworld creators that served as the unconferences proceedings. Each of these outputs shared a common focus on addressing challenges in helping families prepare to face climate risks. The guidance and recommendations contained within the toolkit reflect the collective views and input of the more than 80 professionals (from fields such as climate science, children's media, museums, and child development) that attended the unconference.


Intellectual Merit:


BlackRep4Kids created a cross-disciplinary community of practice dedicated to guiding the production of climate-based STEM stories that affirm Black life, Black futures, and Black relationships with the natural world. Through collaboration and knowledge exchange, the members of this community of practice developed a range of materials (including a podcast series, a resource library, a newsletter series, a research-to-practice brief, and a media makers toolkit) that served to:

Expand understanding of both the disproportionate impacts of climate change on Black communities and the solutions, innovations, and responses that Black communities are developing in response to a multitude of environmental threats;
Articulate and highlight the climate-related needs, hopes, and dreams of Black communities;
Formulate and share strategies for overcoming Black underrepresentation in childrens climate change literature;
Advance best practices for talking about climate science, environmental justice, and other related topics within Black families and communities;
Develop opportunities and capacities for pursuing collaborative, cross-disciplinary climate action aimed at countering anti-Blackness in childrens media and informal learning spaces.



Broader Impacts:


In achieving the above outcomes, BlackRep4Kids contributed to the broader project of building effective climate risk preparedness strategies within Black families and communities. By connecting researchers, educators, and media makers, the project helped build a network of people and resources that support childrens STEM learning in ways that speak to Black childrens experiences (both lived and anticipated) of climate change. In addition to supporting hopeful, emancipatory, solutions-oriented responses to the social, psychological, emotional, and material impacts of climate change, this pipeline positioned climate media as a vehicle for advancing Black childrens acquisition of STEM-related knowledge, concepts, and skills. By promoting greater Black participation in STEM, the project is strengthening ongoing movements to reverse the severe underrepresentation of Black and Brown people in public discussions of climate change  and in decision-making processes related to climate action.





